## What NOT to edit (synced surfaces)

If this repo consumes synced files from an upstream (check for
`.github/workflows/sync-from-upstream.yml`), those files are overwritten on
every sync — local edits are lost. The canonical list lives in the upstream's
sync manifest; adjust the entries below to match what your sync workflow pulls.

Common synced surfaces:

- `.claude/skills/**`
- `.claude/agents/**`
- `.claude/REVIEW_WORKFLOW.md`
- `.claude/settings.json`
- `.github/copilot-instructions.md`

If your issue requires changing any of these, **stop, comment on the issue that
the change belongs upstream, classify the bail (below), and exit without a
commit.** Don't edit the consumer copy — it'll be reverted on the next sync.

## Filesystem hygiene

- Use repo-scoped `/tmp` paths: `/tmp/<repo-name>/...` rather than bare
  `/tmp/foo` to avoid collisions across parallel sessions on the same machine.

## Out-of-scope guardrails

If you discover any of these mid-issue, **stop, comment on the issue, classify
the bail (see below), and exit without a commit**:

- **Issue title starts with `Epic:`, contains `extractable as @`, or otherwise
  reads as cross-repo coordination work.** Epics are tracking issues, not
  bounded implementation tasks. Bail at the title.
- The issue requires touching another repository (cross-repo coordination).
- The deliverable is not code — "submit a form to a regulator," "procure a
  certificate," "rotate a production secret," a signed PDF, or an email to a
  government mailbox. A short comment back is enough.
- The issue has open policy questions — if the body asks "should we A or B?" or
  "decision needed," that's a human call.
- The issue requires deleting org-level secrets, modifying branch protection, or
  installing GitHub Apps — organization-wide blast radius needs human
  verification.
- Acceptance criteria can't be satisfied without changing the synced surfaces
  listed above.

## Continuous improvement — classify every bail

This loop pairs with the **`/backlog-refinement`** skill to form a learning
system: refinement curates the `dev: agent` queue you pull from, and **every
bail teaches the system where the backlog or the loop fell short.** The shared
rubric is `.claude/skills/backlog-refinement/RUBRIC.md` (§3 lists the
`agent-bail:` taxonomy; §4 is this protocol). So when you exit _without a
commit_, before exiting:

1. **Pick the dominant `agent-bail:` category** (one label; mention any
   secondary reasons in your comment):
   - `agent-bail: stale` — the described work already shipped / the issue is out
     of date vs the integration branch HEAD.
   - `agent-bail: spec-gap` — under-specified; you can't determine done-ness.
   - `agent-bail: cross-repo` — needs another repo / an unpublished or private
     dependency / an unmerged upstream change.
   - `agent-bail: open-decision` — unresolved design/product/policy question; a
     human must decide.
   - `agent-bail: credential-gate` — requires a gated build / credential /
     secret / ruleset access.
   - `agent-bail: synced-surface` — acceptance requires editing a
     synced-from-upstream file (belongs upstream).
   - `agent-bail: epic` — tracking/coordination issue, not a bounded task.
   - `agent-bail: loop-mechanics` — the issue _was_ agent-shaped but the run hit
     an avoidable mechanical failure (tooling/env gap, prompt ambiguity,
     transient infra).
   - _(plus any repo-specific sensitive-path category your `RUBRIC.md` §3
     defines.)_
2. **Relabel:** `gh issue edit <N> --add-label "agent-bail: <category>" --add-label "agent: refined" --remove-label "dev: agent"`.
   (Removing `dev: agent` stops the loop re-picking it and is itself a
   high-signal RCA trigger.)
3. **End your issue comment with the RCA stub** so the post-run
   `/backlog-refinement rca` pass can aggregate it:

   ```
   <!-- agent-loop-rca
   category: <agent-bail category>
   bucket: A|B
   preventable: yes|no
   what-could-differ: <one line — the answer, or "nothing: inherent">
   rubric-impact: <which RUBRIC §2 transformation or §3 disqualifier this sharpens>
   -->
   ```

Bucket **A** (`stale` / `spec-gap` / `loop-mechanics`) = preventable; a bail
here means refinement or the loop should have caught it. Bucket **B** (the rest)
= inherent; the issue is correctly not agent-shaped. Be honest about which. (If
`/backlog-refinement` isn't installed in this repo, still comment and exit; just
skip the relabel.)

## Recovery

On command failure, do not reset, clean, stash, reuse, or delete the worktree.
Inspect it and exit non-zero. The wrapper preserves dirty and committed work and
prints recovery instructions.
